name: chicagotribune
text:
RT @John_Kass: How to drive politics out of your head before Christmas? Make my onion soup. It's all about the stock. My "What are you cooking for Christmas Dinner?"column @chicagotribune
https://t.co/NYe6J4IYjH

name: chicagotribune
text: The sandwich is made of two slices of Spam and Oreo cookies, topped with mayonnaise. https://t.co/cmNT0Sap7b

name: chicagotribune
text: “I ran the Chicago Marathon before, and this is like the marathon that never ends. Nurses are just running on fumes right now. I want to say that I’m numb. I don’t feel anything. I’m just going through the motions, just to get it done.” https://t.co/29CjFLqekl

name: chicagotribune
text: A week after the first shipment of Pfizer’s coronavirus vaccine arrived in Illinois, about 63,000 health care workers across the state have received their first of two doses of the immunization, Gov. J.B. Pritzker’s office said. https://t.co/BK19D2VmSi

name: chicagotribune
text: A federal advisory panel has voted to put people 75 and older and essential workers like firefighters, teachers and grocery store workers next in line for the COVID-19 vaccine. https://t.co/zIBsozOoCO

name: chicagotribune
text: The House easily passed a $900 billion COVID-19 relief package Monday night. A Senate vote is expected soon. https://t.co/0zm3zPg2m1

name: chicagotribune
text: Shoe retailers say they’re confident business will bounce back. But some think a shift to more casual looks, already underway before COVID-19, is here to stay. https://t.co/GWlX69cVsZ

name: chicagotribune
text: Fox News, Newsmax shoot down aired election claims after voting machine companies threaten legal action https://t.co/EDVQav9T17

name: chicagotribune
text: The arrival of the two-week winter break amid worrisome COVID-19 rates across the region is adding up to a holiday season fraught with anxiety and uncertainty about what school will look like when classes resume in January. https://t.co/SAC81c28Mp

name: chicagotribune
text: Bring on the December holidays ... during a pandemic. https://t.co/COwsB6HqS3

name: chicagotribune
text: Dozens of email accounts at the Treasury Department were compromised in a massive breach of U.S. agencies being blamed on Russia, with hackers breaking into systems used by the department’s highest-ranking officials, a senator said. https://t.co/J6Wfjbqiie

name: chicagotribune
text: A program that has pumped $2.7 billion into healing long-term injuries to the Great Lakes environment has received authorization from Congress to continue another five years. https://t.co/4w56rzuJvi

name: chicagotribune
text: Trump administration political appointees tried to block or change more than a dozen government reports that detailed scientific findings about the spread of the coronavirus, a House panel investigating the alleged interference said. https://t.co/yzGqHPMqZl

name: chicagotribune
text: Cook County becomes largest U.S. county by population to officially recognize Juneteenth as a paid holiday for its employees https://t.co/VF4HvDN3oE

name: chicagotribune
text: Congress passed a $900 billion pandemic relief package that would finally deliver long-sought cash to businesses and individuals and resources to vaccinate a nation confronting a frightening surge in COVID-19 cases and deaths. https://t.co/h1IAUNGqKU

name: chicagotribune
text: The United States is on track to see more than 3.2 million deaths this year — at least 400,000 more than in 2019 — preliminary numbers show. The increase is due mainly to the COVID-19 pandemic. https://t.co/4U8It5bSMG

name: chicagotribune
text: The Vatican said that it is “morally acceptable” for Catholics to receive COVID-19 vaccines based on research that used fetal tissue from abortions. https://t.co/kqiMpB6l9x

name: chicagotribune
text:
Is it safe to visit the dentist during the coronavirus pandemic?

With coronavirus cases at an all-time high, some patients are nervous. https://t.co/2vVhhGFizL

name: chicagotribune
text: At Cabrini-Green, the new Chicago bumps up against the old, and divisions have grown stark. A child’s killing has put a spotlight on the changing neighborhood. https://t.co/9eu6QUmCsE

name: chicagotribune
text: Chicago Mayor Lori Lightfoot said Black people nationwide "feel angry and feel violated" by the city’s treatment of Anjanette Young and promised to do better. https://t.co/qdqgTCt9xr

name: chicagotribune
text: An Illinois woman who ordered flags for her grandmother’s garden from Wisconsin-based department store chain Kohl’s got someone’s apparent COVID-19 test specimen along with them. The company apologized for “this very unusual and inexplicable experience.” https://t.co/RPmHv5aIds

name: chicagotribune
text: At least 59 incarcerated people have died since March in Illinois’ custody — a death toll that has nearly doubled since November. https://t.co/j4Gl0bAu17
